in: Gunpla

Master Grade

Sign in to edit
  • View history
  • Talk (47)

Master Grade (MG) (マスターグレード, Masutā Gurēdo?) is a line of 1/100 scale Gunpla kits of the Mobile Suits in the Gundam meta series. The series was first produced in 1995 as part of the Gundam 15th Anniversary project.[1]

Master Grade kits differ from other 1/100 scale Gunpla, with their level of detail, articulation, and proportions being second only to the Perfect Grade line. A majority of MG kits feature a skeletal inner frame with working hydraulics, some also accommodate Gunpla LED Units for light-up gimmicks. To give viewers a perspective of the Mobile Suit's size, many MG kits come with 1/100 scale figurines of the pilots or key characters of their respective series. In addition, some kits include 1/20 scale character figures.

Beginning in 2002, veteran mecha designer Hajime Katoki began redesigning various Mobile Suits and releasing them in the Master Grade line under the label of "Ver.Ka" (Version Katoki). Some of the Ver.Ka kits were produced as a result of annual fan votes. In addition, many Mobile Suits from the Universal Century and Cosmic Era timelines have received redesigns under the monikers "Ver.1.5", "Ver.2.0", "Ver.3.0", and "Ver.RM".

In 2020, Bandai created a new sub-line Master Grade Extreme (MGEX),[2] which features "Extreme Points", additional gimmicks such as custom lighting units. The sub-line also has its own Ver.Ka kits.

Aside from the Gundam franchise, the Master Grade line has hosted other mecha anime series such as Aura Battler Dunbine and Mobile Police Patlabor. The line also has a spin-off line called Master Grade Figurise, which focuses on character kits for anime titles such as Dragon Ball Z, One Piece, and Tiger & Bunny, as well as tokusatsu titles such as Kamen Rider.

Following the reorganization of Bandai Namco Group, box covers of reissue and future release of kits from September 2018 onwards feature blue Bandai logo instead of the original red logo, while releases and reissues from mid-2022 onwards feature the Bandai Namco logo on the upper right or lower left corner.

Notes[]

  • MG kits from 1995 to 1998 included heavyuser parts that could be cemented to the armor panels for added detail.
  • Older MG kits before 2006 that have been reissued in the 2010s use the 2006 SB-1 Beam Saber runner in place of the original runner. The original runner's mold has been decommissioned due to reaching its limit for usage.
  • This grade introduced a trend of Bandai model kits being packaged in monochrome box covers when sold exclusively through Premium Bandai. Most P-Bandai kits are variations of existing retail kits and lack the design budget associated with retail kits, so along with the monochrome box covers, these kits lack their own lore sections and artwork, but instead use composited photographs. They often also do not have their own manuals, but instead are packaged with the manual of the retail kit of which they are based on, along with a loose supplementary page detailing the differences.
    • The exceptions to these are "Ver.Ka" models and other kits that feature a high number of new molds or design elements, such as MG F90 Gundam F90 and F90II-I Gundam F90II I-Type. This indicates these kits were designed with a higher budget, similar to retail release kits, rather than traditional P-Bandai products.
    • Some kits are exclusive to P-Bandai only in Japan, and are sold as regular retail kits in other regions. These kits would also receive same treatment as any other retail kit.
    • The remaining exceptions are P-Bandai original releases or kits that feature an intermediate number of new molds or design elements. They would have their own manuals and artwork, though would still be in monochrome.
  • As of mid-November 2022, the Regild Century and Ad Stella are the only major timelines to lack any MG kits.
